Claims WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. An artificial meniscus comprising: a peripheral edge, an interior edge, anterior and posterior horns, an inferior surface, and a superior surface; a polymer material; at least one circumferential fiber bundle; and at least one non-circumferential fiber bundle; wherein the at least one circumferential fiber bundle and the at least one non- circumferential fiber bundle are each embedded in the polymer material, the non-circumferential fiber bundle fully encapsulated within the polymer material, and the circumferential fiber bundle extending out of anterior and posterior horns of the artificial meniscus and terminating in ends that are configured for fixation to bone. 2. The artificial meniscus of claim 1 , further comprising multiple circumferential fiber bundles spaced from each other in the Z-direction. 3. The artificial meniscus of either one of claim 1 or claim 2, wherein the multiple circumferential fiber bundles spaced from each other in the Z-direction are positioned adjacent to the peripheral edge of the artificial meniscus. 4. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-3, further comprising multiple circumferential fiber bundles spaced between the peripheral and interior edges of the artificial meniscus. 5. The artificial meniscus of claim 4, wherein the multiple circumferential fiber bundles converge as they approach the anterior and posterior horns of the artificial meniscus. 6. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-5, wherein the combined ultimate tensile strength of the at least one circumferential fiber bundle is at least 12 MPa. 7. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-6, wherein the at least one non- circumferential fiber bundle is part of woven sheet of fiber bundles. 8. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-7, further comprising multiple non- circumferential fiber bundles spaced from each other in the Z-direction. 9. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-8, wherein the at least one non- circumferential fiber bundle is positioned adjacent a superior surface or an inferior surface of the artificial meniscus, and wherein the non-circumferential fiber bundle follows the curvature of the adjacent superior or inferior surface. 10. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-9, wherein the combined ultimate tensile strength of the at least one non-circumferential fiber is at least 1 MPa. 11. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-10, wherein the at least one non- circumferential fiber bundle extends in a radial direction. 12. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-11, further comprising a plurality of radially extending, non-circumferential fiber bundles spaced across the artificial meniscus between the anterior horn and the posterior horn. 13. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-12, wherein the at least one non- circumferential fiber bundle extends back and forth in an at least partially curved line from positions near the peripheral surface of the artificial meniscus to positions near the interior surface of the artificial meniscus. 14. The artificial meniscus of claim 13, wherein the at least one non-circumferential fiber bundle curves continuously between a first end and a second end. 15. The artificial meniscus of claim 13, wherein the at least one non-circumferential fiber bundle alternates between curved segments near the peripheral and interior surfaces of the 

 artificial meniscus and straight segments between the peripheral and interior surfaces of the artificial meniscus. 16. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-15, wherein the artificial meniscus can sustain at least 100N of tensile load for 1000 cycles under cyclic tension testing without altering the ultimate tensile strength or tensile modulus. 17. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-16, wherein the artificial meniscus has a compressive modulus of less than 100 MPa. 18. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-17, wherein the artificial meniscus has a shear strength of at least 0.75 MPa. 19. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-18, wherein the polymer material is a uniform, continuous structure surrounding the at least one circumferential fiber bundle and the at least one non-circumferential fiber bundle. 20. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-19, wherein both the circumferential and non-circumferential fiber bundles are formed from a synthetic material. 21. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1-20, wherein the polymer material penetrates individual fibers of the circumferential and non-circumferential fiber bundles. 22. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 1- 21, wherein the polymer material is a hydrogel. 23. The artificial meniscus of claim 22, wherein the hydrogel comprises at least 20% water by weight. 24. The artificial meniscus of any one of claims 21-23, wherein the artificial meniscus has a fiber tear out strength of at least 140 Newtons. 25. A method of implanting the device of any one of claims 1-24, the method comprising: threading a first end of the circumferential fiber bundle extending from the anterior horn through a first bone tunnel; threading a second end of the circumferential fiber bundle extending from the posterior horn through a second bone tunnel; and immobilizing the first and second ends of the circumferential fiber bundles with respect to an adjacent bone. 26. The method of claim 25, wherein immobilizing the first and second ends of the circumferential fiber bundle further comprises tying the first and second ends to each other. 27. The method of either one of claims 25 or 26, wherein immobilizing the first and second ends of the circumferential fiber bundle further comprises affixing each of the first and second ends to a button -like structure. 28. The method of either one of claims 25 or 26, wherein immobilizing the first and second ends of the circumferential fiber bundle further comprises affixing each of the first and second ends to an interference screw. 29. A method of making a meniscus-shaped article, the method comprising: partially encapsulating at least one circumferential fiber bundle in a first bulk polymer precursor while allowing ends of the at least one circumferential fiber bundle to exit the first bulk polymer precursor; setting the first bulk polymer precursor, thereby forming a first intermediate component of the meniscus-shaped article; fully encapsulating at least one non-circumferential bundle into a second bulk polymer precursor such that all ends of the non-circumferential fiber bundle are covered by the second bulk polymer precursor; 

 setting the second bulk polymer precursor, thereby forming a second intermediate component of the meniscus-shaped article; arranging the first and second intermediate components within a meniscus-shaped mold; surrounding the first and second intermediate components with a third bulk polymer precursor within the meniscus-shaped mold; and setting the third bulk polymer precursor, thereby forming the meniscus-shaped article. 30. The method of claim 29, wherein setting the first bulk polymer precursor further comprises forming the first intermediate component in a curved shape prior to arranging the first intermediate component within the meniscus-shaped mold. 31. The method of either one of claim 29 or claim 30, wherein setting the second bulk polymer precursor further comprises forming the second intermediate component in the shape of a sheet prior to arranging the second intermediate component within the meniscus-shaped mold. 32. The method of any one of claims 29-31 , wherein the material of the first bulk polymer precursor, the second bulk polymer precursor, and the third bulk polymer precursor are the same. 33. The method of any one of claims 29-32, wherein setting of the first bulk polymer precursor, the second bulk polymer precursor, and the third bulk polymer is accomplished by freeze-thaw cycling. 34. The method of any one of claims 29-33, further comprising layering a bottom layer of bulk polymer precursor into the meniscus-shaped mold prior to arranging the first and/or second intermediate components 35. The method of claim 34, further comprising setting the bottom layer of bulk polymer precursor prior to arranging the first and/or second intermediate components. 36. The method of claim 34 or 35, wherein the bottom layer of bulk polymer precursor is the same material as the first bulk polymer precursor, the second bulk polymer precursor, and the third bulk polymer precursor. 37. The method of any one of claims 29-36, further comprising layering a top layer of bulk polymer precursor into the meniscus-shaped mold after arranging the first and/or second intermediate components. 38. The method of claim 37, wherein the top layer of bulk polymer precursor is the third bulk polymer precursor. 39. The method of claim 37, wherein the top layer of bulk polymer precursor is separate from the third bulk polymer precursor, and the method further comprises setting the top layer of bulk polymer precursor. 40. The method of any one of claims 37-39, wherein the top layer of bulk polymer precursor is the same material as the first bulk polymer precursor, the second bulk polymer precursor, and the third bulk polymer precursor.
